we said we have all the file project on every commit completely!
so we can restore some file from a far commit!
imaging we are removed some file and make commit,
but we want to restore it
(but because we make commit we have not that file on last commit)
we should bring back that file from some older commit.

1. I remove the first file of this section (initiate 1)         rm initiate\ 1
   and make commit                                              git add .
                                                                git commit -m "removing initiate 1"

2.we want to restore it, but it not exist on last commit!
  at first we need a commit that contain our file
  so we use history:
  git log --oneline                                 30c6b95 (HEAD -> main) removing initiate 1
                                                    756d4d7 undo working directory
  the second commit after last                      52af8cf staging
  commit is good  (756d4d7)                         8da0ac7 unstaging
                                                    afbf06a find a commit
                                                    8e55fd3 git log
                                                    19ca155 set visual compare


3.restore the file from that commit:
  git restore --source=HEAD~1 "initiate 1"

Note: we can find this from help!
      git restore -h will introduce the argument of the command:

      git restore [<options>] [--source=<branch>] <file>...     //[<options>] that introduce below
                                                                //[--source=<branch>] means witch branch(commit)?
                                                                //by default it is last commit, so we change it
                                                                //<file> means use file name!

Note: it will restore it to working directory       ?? "initiate 1"
      so it does not exist on stage yet
      so it is untracked file yet!

